[[File:Apimeleki Qiliho.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Apimeleki Qiliho (Bishop of Vanua Levu and Taveuni)]]
'''Apimeleki Nadoki Qiliho''' is an [[indigenous peoples|indigenous]] [[Fijians|Fijian]] from the [[Province]] of [[Nadroga-Navosa]] in the [[Fiji|Fiji Islands]]. He is the [[Anglican Communion|Anglican]] "[[Bishop]] in [[Vanua Levu]] and [[Taveuni]]"<ref>[http://www.anglican.org.nz/Directory/Diocese-of-Polynesia/Diocese-of-Polynesia Directory: Diocese of Polynesia]</ref> in the [[Diocese of Polynesia]] or '''Tikanga Pasefika''' under the [[Anglican Church in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia]]. He made church history by becoming the first indigenous Fijian Bishop in the Anglican Church<ref name=first>{{cite web| url = http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO0507/S00022.htm | title = First indigenous Fijian bishop for Anglican Church | accessdate = 2010-07-30 | date = 2005-07-04 | publisher = ''[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]]''}}</ref> in Aotearoa, New Zealand and Polynesia. He is one of three [[Episcopal]]{{Disambiguation needed|date=June 2011}} or suffragan bishops who serve under the [[Archbishop]] of Polynesia, [[Jabez Bryce]]. This diocese covers [[Fiji]], [[Samoa]], [[Tonga]] and the [[Cook Islands]]. Apimeleki Qiliho serves as area bishop over the Vanua Levu and Taveuni Episcopal Area. The other two Bishops in the Diocese of Polynesia are [[Gabriel Sharma]], Bishop of [[Viti Levu]] West and Winston Halapua, the diocesan bishop who serves [[Polynesians]] in [[New Zealand]].

== Background ==
Qiliho comes from the village of Rukurukulevu in the district of Cuvu in [[Nadroga-Navosa|Nadroga]],<ref name=first/> located in Fiji's [[Western Division, Fiji|Western Division]]. He then spent some time living in [[Lautoka]], the capital of the Western Division, at which time he changed denomination from being [[Methodist Church of Fiji and Rotuma|Methodist]] to an Anglican. He than decided to become a priest and eventually was made a Bishop after serving for some time as the [[Vicar general]] at [[Holy Trinity Cathedral]] in Suva. Apimeleki Qiliho lives in [[Labasa]] on Vanua Levu and is currently married to Taomi Tapu Qiliho. He was previously married to Litiana Rika who died in 1997. He has four children and eight grandchildren.

== Career ==

Qiliho began training to be an Anglican priest in the early 1960s and during the course of his training stayed in Suva and [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand. After becoming a priest he had postings to [[parish]]es around Fiji such as [[Levuka]], etc. He than went on to become Vicar General under Bishop Jabez Bryce and then Bishop of Vanua Levu and Taveuni. He also has served on many church and non church organisations such as the Pacific Council Of Churches,The Fiji Council of Churches and the President of the Pacific/ Fiji Bible Society. He also does work with certain [[AIDS]], [[youth]] and [[NGO|non governmental]] [[organisations]] in Fiji and the region. Apimeleki Qiliho also, on occasion, writes columns for the ''[[Fiji Times]]'' newspaper.

